# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: purdue-model-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] In computer security, a **DMZ** or **demilitarized zone** (sometimes referred to as a **perimeter network** or screened subnet) is a physical or logical subnetwork that contains and exposes an organization's external-facing services to an untrusted, usually larger, network such as the Internet.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The purpose of a DMZ is to add an additional layer of security to an organization's local area network (LAN): an external network node can access only what is exposed in the DMZ, while the rest of the organization's network is protected behind a firewall.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The DMZ functions as a small, isolated network positioned between the Internet and the private network.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] This is not to be confused with a **DMZ host**, a feature present in some home routers that frequently differs greatly from an ordinary DMZ.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The name is from the term *demilitarized zone*, an area between states in which military operations are not permitted.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The DMZ is seen as not belonging to either network bordering it.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] This metaphor applies to the computing use as the DMZ acts as a gateway to the public Internet.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] It is neither as secure as the internal network nor as insecure as the public internet.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] In this case, the hosts most vulnerable to attack are those that provide services to users outside of the local area network, such as e-mail, Web and Domain Name System (DNS) servers.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Because of the increased potential of these hosts suffering an attack, they are placed into this specific subnetwork in order to protect the rest of the network in case any of them become compromised.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Hosts in the DMZ are permitted to have only limited connectivity to specific hosts in the internal network, as the content of DMZ is not as secure as the internal network.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Similarly, communication between hosts in the DMZ and to the external network is also restricted to make the DMZ more secure than the Internet and suitable for housing these special-purpose services.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] This allows hosts in the DMZ to communicate with both the internal and external network, while an intervening firewall controls the traffic between the DMZ servers and the internal network clients, and another firewall would perform some level of control to protect the DMZ from the external network.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] A DMZ configuration provides additional security from external attacks, but it typically has no bearing on internal attacks such as sniffing communication via a packet analyzer or spoofing, such as e-mail spoofing.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] In such architecture, the DMZ usually has the application firewall and the FTP while the CMZ hosts the Web servers.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Any service that is being provided to users on the external network can be placed in the DMZ.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Web servers that communicate with an internal database require access to a database server, which may not be publicly accessible and may contain sensitive information.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The web servers can communicate with database servers either directly or through an application firewall for security reasons.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] E-mail messages and particularly the user database are confidential, so they are typically stored on servers that cannot be accessed from the Internet (at least not in an insecure manner), but can be accessed from email servers that are exposed to the Internet.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The mail server inside the DMZ passes incoming mail to the secured/internal mail servers.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] For security, compliance with legal standards such as HIPAA, and monitoring reasons, in a business environment, some enterprises install a proxy server within the DMZ.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] A reverse proxy server, like a proxy server, is an intermediary but is used the other way around.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Instead of providing a service to internal users wanting to access an external network, it provides indirect access for an external network (usually the Internet) to internal resources.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] This is an extra layer of security particularly recommended when internal resources need to be accessed from the outside, but it's worth noting this design still allows remote (and potentially malicious) users to talk to the internal resources with the help of the proxy.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] There are many different ways to design a network with a DMZ.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Two of the most basic methods are with a single firewall, also known as the three-legged model, and with dual firewalls, also known as back to back.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] These architectures can be expanded to create very complex architectures depending on the network requirements.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] A single firewall with at least 3 network interfaces can be used to create a network architecture containing a DMZ.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The external network is formed from the Internet service provider to the firewall on the first network interface, the internal network is formed from the second network interface, and the DMZ is formed from the third network interface.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The firewall becomes a single point of failure for the network and must be able to handle all of the traffic going to the DMZ as well as the internal network.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The zones are usually marked with colors -for example, purple for LAN, green for DMZ, red for Internet (with often another color used for wireless zones).
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The most secure approach, according to Colton Fralick, is to use two firewalls to create a DMZ.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The first firewall (also called the "front-end" or "perimeter" firewall) must be configured to allow traffic destined to the DMZ only.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The second firewall (also called "back-end" or "internal" firewall) only allows traffic to the DMZ from the internal network.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] This setup is considered more secure since two devices would need to be compromised.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] There is even more protection if the two firewalls are provided by two different vendors, because it makes it less likely that both devices suffer from the same security vulnerabilities.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] For example, a security hole found to exist in one vendor's system is less likely to occur in the other one.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] One of the drawbacks of this architecture is that it's more costly, both to purchase and to manage.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The practice of using different firewalls from different vendors is sometimes described as a component of a "defense in depth" security strategy.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] Some routers have a feature called **DMZ host**.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] This feature could designate one node (PC or other device with an IP address) as a DMZ host.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] The router's firewall exposes all ports on the DMZ host to the external network and hinders no inbound traffic from the outside going to the DMZ host.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] This is a less secure alternative to port forwarding, which only exposes a handful of ports.
[src:purdue-model-security/demilitarized-zone-computing] In all but the first scenario above, the DMZ host feature is used outside a true DMZ configuration.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] An **industrial control system** (**ICS**) is an electronic control system and associated instrumentation used for industrial process control.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems can range in size from a few modular panel-mounted controllers to large interconnected and interactive distributed control systems (DCSs) with many thousands of field connections.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems receive data from remote sensors measuring process variables (PVs), compare the collected data with desired setpoints (SPs), and derive command functions that are used to control a process through the final control elements (FCEs), such as control valves.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Larger systems are usually implemented by supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems, or DCSs, and programmable logic controllers (PLCs), though SCADA and PLC systems are scalable down to small systems with few control loops.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Such systems are extensively used in industries such as chemical processing, pulp and paper manufacture, power generation, oil and gas processing, and telecommunications.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The simplest control systems are based around small discrete controllers with a single control loop each.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] These are usually panel mounted, which allows direct viewing of the front panel and provides a means of manual intervention by the operator, either to manually control the process or to change control setpoints.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Originally, these would be pneumatic controllers, a few of which are still in use, but nearly all are now electronic.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Quite complex systems can be created with networks of these controllers communicating using industry-standard protocols.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Networking allows the use of local or remote SCADA operator interfaces and enables the cascading and interlocking of controllers.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] However, as the number of control loops increases for a system design, there is a point where the use of a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS) is more manageable or cost-effective.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] A distributed control system (DCS) is a digital process control system (PCS) for a process or plant, wherein controller functions and field connection modules are distributed throughout the system.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] As the number of control loops grows, DCS becomes more cost effective than discrete controllers.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, a DCS provides supervisory viewing and management over large industrial processes.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] In a DCS, a hierarchy of controllers is connected by communication networks, allowing centralized control rooms and local on-plant monitoring and control.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS enables easy configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other computer systems such as production control.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] It also enables more sophisticated alarm handling, introduces automatic event logging, removes the need for physical records such as chart recorders and allows the control equipment to be networked and thereby located locally to the equipment being controlled to reduce cabling.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS typically uses custom-designed processors as controllers and uses either proprietary interconnections or standard protocols for communication.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Input and output modules form the peripheral components of the system.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be performed by the output modules.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The input modules receive information from sensing instruments in the process (or field) and the output modules transmit instructions to the final control elements, such as control valves.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can either be continuously changing analog signals, e.g., current loop or 2-state signals that switch either *on* or *off*, such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Distributed control systems can normally also support Foundation Fieldbus, PROFIBUS, HART, Modbus and other digital communication buses that carry not only input and output signals but also advanced messages such as error diagnostics and status signals.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is a control system architecture that uses computers, networked data communications and graphical user interfaces for high-level process supervisory management.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA supervisory computer system.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] However, the real-time control logic or controller calculations are performed by networked modules which connect to other peripheral devices such as programmable logic controllers and discrete PID controllers which interface to the process plant or machinery.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA concept was developed as a universal means of remote access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers, allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become very similar to distributed control systems in function, but using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] They can control large-scale processes that can include multiple sites and work over large distances.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] This is a commonly used architecture industrial control systems, however there are concerns about SCADA systems being vulnerable to cyberwarfare or cyberterrorism attacks.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA software operates on a supervisory level as control actions are performed automatically by RTUs or PLCs.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA control functions are usually restricted to basic overriding or supervisory level intervention.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] A feedback control loop is directly controlled by the RTU or PLC, but the SCADA software monitors the overall performance of the loop.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] For example, a PLC may control the flow of cooling water through part of an industrial process to a set point level, but the SCADA system software will allow operators to change the set points for the flow.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA also enables alarm conditions, such as loss of flow or high temperature, to be displayed and recorded.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O) in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Initially, control was from panels local to the process plant.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] However, this required personnel to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Often, the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were individually transmitted back to the plant in the form of pneumatic or electrical signals.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Effectively, this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of reduced manpower requirements and a consolidated overview of the process.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, so system changes required reconfiguration of signals by re-piping or re-wiring.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] It also required continual operator movement within a large control room in order to monitor the whole process.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors, high-speed electronic signalling networks and electronic graphic displays, it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] These could be distributed around the plant and would communicate with the graphic displays in the control room.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The concept of *distributed control* was realised.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The introduction of distributed control allowed flexible interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] For large control systems, the general commercial name *distributed control system* (DCS) was coined to refer to proprietary modular systems from many manufacturers that integrated high-speed networking and a full suite of displays and control racks.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] While the DCS was tailored to meet the needs of large continuous industrial processes, in industries where combinatorial and sequential logic was the primary requirement, the PLC evolved out of a need to replace racks of relays and timers used for event-driven control.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The old controls were difficult to reconfigure and debug, and PLC control enabled networking of signals to a central control area with electronic displays.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs were first developed for the automotive industry on vehicle production lines, where sequential logic was becoming very complex.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] It was soon adopted in a large number of other event-driven applications as varied as printing presses and water treatment plants.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA's history is rooted in distribution applications, such as power, natural gas, and water pipelines, where there is a need to gather remote data through potentially unreliable or intermittent low-bandwidth and high-latency links.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA systems use open-loop control with sites that are widely separated geographically.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] A SCADA system uses remote terminal units (RTUs) to send supervisory data back to a control centre.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Most RTU systems always had some capacity to handle local control while the master station is not available.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] However, over the years, RTU systems have grown more and more capable of handling local control.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The boundaries between DCS and SCADA/PLC systems are blurring as time goes on.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The technical limits that drove the designs of these various systems are no longer as much of an issue.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Many PLC platforms can now perform quite well as a small DCS, using remote I/O and are sufficiently reliable that some SCADA systems actually manage closed-loop control over long distances.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] With the increasing speed of today's processors, many DCS products have a full line of PLC-like subsystems that weren't offered when they were initially developed.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] In 1993, with the release of IEC-1131, later to become IEC-61131-3, the industry moved towards increased code standardization with reusable, hardware-independent control software.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] For the first time, object-oriented programming (OOP) became possible within industrial control systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] This led to the development of both programmable automation controllers (PAC) and industrial PCs (IPC).
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] These are platforms programmed in the five standardized IEC languages: ladder logic, structured text, function block, instruction list and sequential function chart.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] They can also be programmed in modern high-level languages such as C or C++.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, they accept models developed in analytical tools such as MATLAB and Simulink.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Unlike traditional PLCs, which use proprietary operating systems, IPCs utilize Windows IoT.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] IPCs have the advantage of powerful multi-core processors with much lower hardware costs than traditional PLCs and fit well into multiple form factors such as DIN rail mount, combined with a touch-screen as a panel PC, or as an embedded PC.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] New hardware platforms and technology have contributed significantly to the evolution of DCS and SCADA systems, further blurring the boundaries and changing definitions.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA and PLCs are vulnerable to cyber attack.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] Government Joint Capability Technology Demonstration (JCTD) known as MOSAICS (More Situational Awareness for Industrial Control Systems) is the initial demonstration of cybersecurity defensive capability for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] MOSAICS addresses the Department of Defense (DOD) operational need for cyber defense capabilities to defend critical infrastructure control systems from cyber attack, such as power, water and wastewater, and safety controls, affect the physical environment.
[src:purdue-model-security/industrial-control-system] The MOSAICS JCTD prototype will be shared with commercial industry through Industry Days for further research and development, an approach intended to lead to an innovative, game-changing capabilities for cybersecurity for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] When a cyber-criminal gains unauthorized access to a network, segmentation or “zoning” can provide effective controls to limit further movement across the network.
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] For example separating the network for Payment Card authorizations from those for Point-of-Service (till) or customer Wi-Fi traffic.
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] A sound security policy entails segmenting the network into multiple zones, with varying security requirements, and rigorously enforcing the policy on what is allowed to move from zone to zone.
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] Finance and Human Resources typically need access via their own VLAN to their application servers because of the confidential nature of the information they process and store.
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] Other groups of personnel may require their own segregated networks, such as server administrators, security administration, managers and executives.
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] Third parties are usually required to have their own segments, with different administration passwords to the main network, to avoid attacks via a compromised, less well protected, third party site.
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] Segregation is typically achieved by a combination of firewalls and VLANs (virtual local area networks).
[src:purdue-model-security/network-segmentation] Software-defined networking (SDN) can allow the creation and management of micro-segmented networks.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] The built environment, whether commercial or domestic, is increasingly controlled and monitored via Internet of Things (IoT) and Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) devices.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] In this application space, these IoT devices are both interconnected via converged technology edge IoT platforms and or via "cloud" based applications.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Embedded Systems are also included in the sphere of operational technology (e.g. smart instrumentation), along with a large subset of scientific data acquisition, control, and computing devices.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Systems that process operational data (including electronic, telecommunications, computer systems and technical components) are included under the term operational technology.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] OT systems can be required to control valves, engines, conveyors and other machines to regulate various process values, such as temperature, pressure, flow, and to monitor them to prevent hazardous conditions.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] OT systems use various technologies for hardware design and communications protocols, that are unknown in IT.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Common problems include supporting legacy systems & devices and numerous vendor architectures and standards.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Since OT systems often supervise industrial processes, most of the time availability must be sustained.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] This often means that real time (or near-real time) processing is required, with high rates of reliability and availability.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] This kind of environment may also be referred to as industrial information technology (IIT).
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Historical OT networks utilized proprietary protocols optimized for the required functions, some of which have become adopted as 'standard' industrial communications protocols (e.g.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] DNP3, Modbus, Profibus, LonWorks, DALI, BACnet, KNX, EnOcean and OPC-UA).
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] More recently IT-standard network protocols are being implemented in OT devices and systems to reduce complexity and increase compatibility with more traditional IT hardware (e.g.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] TCP/IP); this however has had a demonstrable reduction in security for OT systems, which in the past have relied on air gaps and the inability to run PC-based malware (see Stuxnet for a well-known example of this change).
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] The term operational technology as applied to industrial control systems was first published in a research paper from Gartner in May 2006 (Steenstrup, Sumic, Spiers, Williams) and presented publicly in September 2006 at the Gartner Energy and Utilities IT Summit.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Initially the term was applied to power utility control systems, but over time was adopted by other industrial sectors and used in combination with IoT.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] A principal driver of the adoption of the term was that the nature of operational technology platforms had evolved from bespoke proprietary systems to complex software portfolios that rely on IT infrastructure.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] This change was termed IT OT convergence.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] The concept of aligning and integrating the IT and OT systems of industrial companies gained importance as companies realized that physical assets and infrastructure was both managed by OT systems but also generated data for the IT systems running the business.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Industrial technology companies such as GE, Hitachi, Honeywell, Siemens, ABB and Rockwell are the main providers of OT platforms and systems either embedded in equipment or added to them for control, management and monitoring.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] These industrial technology companies have needed to evolve into software companies rather than being strictly machine providers.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Security of operational technology systems has historically relied almost entirely on the standalone nature of OT installations, security by obscurity.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] At least since 2005 OT systems have become linked to IT systems with the corporate goal of widening an organization's ability to monitor and adjust its OT systems, which has introduced massive challenges in securing them.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Approaches known from regular IT are usually replaced or redesigned to align with the OT environment.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] The intersection of operational technology and standard networking infrastructure exposes industrial processes to several distinct categories of risk.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Mitigation of these integrated risks typically involves the adoption of multi-layered security frameworks, continuous anomaly monitoring, and adherence to established institutional standards such as the ISA/IEC 62443 series.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Operational technology is widely used in refineries, power plants, nuclear plants, etc. and as such has become a common, crucial element of critical infrastructure systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] Depending on the country, critical infrastructure operators may face increasing legal obligations with regard to the implementation of OT systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] For several decades, hundreds of thousands of buildings have been upgraded with IoT building management, automation and smart lighting control solutions, but many of these solutions lack the proper security measures.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] This has recently led to bad actors exploiting such solutions' vulnerabilities with ransomware attacks causing system lock outs, operational failures exposing businesses operating in such buildings to the immense risks to health and safety, operations, brand reputation and financial damage.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] There is a strong focus put on subjects like IT/OT cooperation or IT/OT alignment in the modern industrial setting.
[src:purdue-model-security/operational-technology] The Stuxnet malware is one example of this, highlighting the potential for disaster should a safety system become infected with malware (whether targeted at that system or accidentally infected).
[src:purdue-model-security/purdue-enterprise-reference-architecture] PERA is a reference architecture that can model the enterprise in multiple layers and in multiple stages of the architectural life cycle.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:purdue-model-security/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
